<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06129e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06129e">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06129e"> 129(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> T&apos;s false vocations</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>La vraie marque d&apos;une vocation</mark> est l&apos;impossibilit&eacute; d&apos;y forfaire, c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire de reaussir &agrave; autre chose que ce pour quoi l&apos;on a &eacute;t&eacute; cr&eacute;&eacute;. L&apos;homme qui a une vocation sacrifie tout involontairement &agrave; sa ma&icirc;tresse &oelig;uvre. Des circonstances ext&eacute;rieures auraient pu, comme il arrive souvent, d&eacute;router ma vi&eacute; et m&apos;emp&ecirc;cher de suivre ma voie naturelle; mais l&apos;absolue incapacit&eacute; o&ugrave; jurais &eacute;t&eacute; de reaussir &agrave; ce qui n&apos;&eacute;tait pas ma destin&eacute;e e&ucirc;t &eacute;t&eacute; la protestation du devoir <font color="green">[74]</font> contrari&eacute;, et la pr&eacute;destination e&ucirc;t triomph&eacute; &agrave; sa mani&egrave;re en montrant le sujet qu&apos;elle avait choisi absolument impuissant en dehors du travail pour lequel elle l&apos;avait choisi. Toute carri&egrave;re ayant pour objet la recherche d&apos;un int&eacute;r&ecirc;t quelconque, j&apos;y aurais &eacute;t&eacute; nul, maladroit, au-dessous du m&eacute;diocre. <font color="green">[The true mark of a vocation is the impossibility of forging it, that is to say of reaffirming something other than what we were created for. The man who has a vocation sacrifices everything involuntarily to his mistress. External circumstances could, as it often happens, divert my life and prevent me from following my natural path; but the absolute incapacity in which I had sworn to reapply to what was not my destiny would have been the protest of duty thwarted, and predestination would have triumphed in its own way by showing the subject which it had chosen absolutely impotent in out of work for which she had chosen it. Any career whose object is the search for any interest, I would have been nil, clumsy, below the mediocre.]</font> <small> Ernest Renan, <a name="ERSD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ERSD"><cite title="source">Souvenirs d'enfance et de jeunesse</cite></a> (1883) 74-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
